Columbus to the Spanish Monarchy in the confused timeline: "You've no understanding how this place should be run, so 
a) I'm going to overthrow you through political scheming
b) ???
c) Discovery of America!"

I did the math on boosting gay bookshops into the sun and it doesn't make economic sense (except in the very long term).

Gross.

... Your grubby retarded shit will never be sorted out, unless as an unplanned side-effect of attained greatness.

Anyone with serious concerns about uncontrolled public debt should be thinking about how relevant political incentives could be fundamentally reconstructed, because there is simply no other way the problem ever gets resolved. ...

... Just demanding that politicians stop being corrupt, pork addicted, economic vandals is entirely useless so long as their political incentives are driving them in exactly that direction. They're not going to come to Jesus. Deep regime design is the whole real problem.
A smoother (more continuous) reward / punishment function would be preferable.
... Crude but directionally sound would be to determine  the salaries of elected officials as some acceptable multiple of the primary budget surplus.
The primary reason to doubt that 'growing out of the debt' could imaginably happen is that no one who matters seriously wants it to. Given sufficient growth, debt ambitions will just be up-scaled.
